```
189    491460.43750  0.00000   0.00000    0.00000    0.00000    0.10329    266353935  0.38605    *     1702       1  34.141.18x.xx:8209     5FxcZraZAC  5GP8N57T2o
```

I don't know - how does the "inference" IP get looked-up in your / whatever code?  Does it support triple NATs?

this is our end goal. each vali will run an instance of targon hub, remember we are an extremely small team, especially compared to other teams on this network and are working as hard as we can to get all these features out
based off the ip that sent the request
Neither of those IPs are the actual Public IP of our machine running for this SN.  I suspect (but not sure) this is because there are *at least* 3 NATs involved here on traffic exiting.
Or, someone is spoofing us or something?
Is this causing <someone> or <something> a problem or is this just a question / curiousity?  I'd like to understand the impact.

I think it's fine - you have a listening IP/port, i.e. serving an axon so requests from outside services can reach your validator, which by default uses the bittensor library's built-in get_external_ip method (and you can override it with `--axon.external_ip a.b.c.d`), but outgoing traffic may or may not route through the same IP as incoming traffic.  I would just double check the external listening IP though to make sure requests can route there.

That said, I (and probably others) often check for incoming request IP difference from metagraph IP to help check request validity, because in the past when validator hotkeys have been compromised, the attacker would forge requests using those compromised hotkeys to relay mine, and metagraph IP vs actual request IP is one of the few ways to check that currently.

Interesting re: checking.  We generally have 3+ NATs on the outbound so our IPs will never match.  This is partially due to security and partially due to how we run things.

We prefer not to set static `axon` vars because they change.  We move things around quite frequently and even if automated, there is further risk of error / confusion.

To summarize: This doesn't sound like a problem for folks - just a difference in how we choose to secure our infrastructure.

Do you notice something similar with other validators?
It's not a problem, just makes security a bit more challenging for miners but solving these things is what we do so NBD.  Yes, we've seen it with other validators; often the same /24 subnet though.

Yea- we don't have everything in the same block unfortunately (and sometimes honestly: fortunately!).  While it is nice to sometimes be able to share an explicit IP for identity - IP spoofing is so darn easy / trivial (especially in metadata) - it is ~useless.
Is there something else, metadata-wise, that would assist miners more broadly we should advocate for with OTF?
yeah the axon up field is fully self reported and I would never ever recommend even checking it in the first place
same goes with almost all of the axon fields tbh
Yea, that is why I am asking- seems... not super fruitful today.
you can however simply check the axon IP:PORT to see if it responds as you'd expect for the subnet to see if it's completely faked or not

really though I would say it's more important for if/when public applications are built on top of the subnet/validators because the metagraph is really the only way to automatically load the validator entrypoints to use
I suppose private DMs with valis would work too but then the transparency is gone
It sounds like there isn't a good option today.  IP is not a good identity unless signed w/metadata and folks guarantee / own the space.
Hosting a piece of cryptographically signed metadata is generally a good solution / what other protocols do.

in theory though, if the validator wasn't intentionally spoofing the IP address, it would be a good solution because you can't publish the axon info in the first place without the private key so it is cryptographically secure (as long as someone doesn't compromise the hotkey), then checking the metagraph against incoming IP is actually secure

There are basically two problems at the moment, which cause this instability:
1. jaro is a bit of a crapshoot, even completely vanilla vllm instances will fail 15% or so of the time depending on validator hardware/software/driver versions/configs vs miner.
2. validators sometimes (quite rarely) send duplicate requests, causing max theoretical TPS to skyrocket

To compete, you really need at least one miner to pass jaro basically every time.  Supposing a jaro fail rate of 0.15, that means you'd need to run about 44 miners to have a > 0.99 probability that one of them passes 15 consecutive requests, but that also requires a lot of hardware.

For the duplicates, the best solution is to prevent it, but that's hard.  I suggested this, which prevents absurdly high scores, but it's not ideal:
https://github.com/manifold-inc/targon/pull/34

# @delta New Update 4.2.3
Should help incentive curve a ton.
## Changes

- Top percentile is now 30% (up from 20%)
- anyone that is successfully responding but not in top 30% will get scored the same at the lowest level. this way as long as your miner is responding youll get *some* weight, so no dereg for miners that are on
- Jaro now looks at the first 3rd, and does a hard check (must pass w/ > .9) and *then* the last 2/3rds, which must match > .55. This increased the passing rate for responses that seemed *good enough* by 5 fold.
- response length must now be 70% as long as ground truth (down from 80%)
- mean calculation for determining weight multiples the mean of passing wps scores by a sigmoid of the percentage of validated responses, shifted to 0 and 1. This allows much more variance in missing 1-3 queries before seeing a massive dropoff in score.

```python
from openai import OpenAI

client = OpenAI(

    ],
)
import time

start_time = time.time()
tokens = 0

for chunk in response:
    if chunk.choices[0].delta.content is not None:
        print(chunk.choices[0].delta.content, end="", flush=True)
        tokens += len(chunk.choices[0].delta.content.split())

end_time = time.time()
elapsed_time = end_time - start_time
tokens_per_second = tokens / elapsed_time if elapsed_time > 0 else 0

print(f"\nTokens per second: {tokens_per_second:.2f}")
```

Not sure this is true.

Anything at ~1000 tokens/s is almost certainly from Groq itself - so we're just wrapping that. The verification method only works for extremely low temperatures, and it only checks the outputs are close to eachother (Jaro). This is why miners could go to Groq and directly use llama 3.1 8B which is indeed available there, and just run it on this subnet. 

Of course it wont work everytime as Groq do some quantisation and stuff like that. So only some of the miners will pass these checks. Which leads to these graphs:

Note, on the second graph i've removed responses with tokens/s > 200, indicitive of Groq or another wrapper - which naturally barely affects the median.

So our median tokens per second in either case is ~80t/s, which makes much more sense.

This is assuming targon runs only on subnet 4 as we're going through a wrapper here.

Here is the equivalent for sn19 where the task gets 15% ~= 1.35% emissions in total. This is much more inline with what we've expect - roughly equivalent of that to subnet 4 (higher median lower mean, roughly the same)
